I've worked around this by using BSON::OrderedHash#delete_if

I set up a new database, and while running my regular setup scripts that runs the commands to shard the database and a few collections in it I got a very strange error.

The setup script never got as far as sending the sharding commands, it failed at creating indexes.

I can repeat the problem with the following code:

{noformat}
require 'mongo'

c = Mongo::Connection.new('localhost', 31000)
db = c.db('fragments_20110831')
cl = db.collection('xyz')
cl.ensure_index([[:split_key, 1], [:_id, 1]]
{noformat}

which raises the following error:

{noformat}
Mongo::OperationFailure: Failed to create index {:name=>"split_key_1__id_1", :ns=>"fragments_20110831.xyz", :key=>{"split_key"=>1, "_id"=>1}} with the following error: : isOk()
  generate_indexes at /usr/local/rvm/gems/jruby-1.6.2@rich_collection/gems/mongo-1.3.1/lib/../lib/mongo/collection.rb:857
      ensure_index at /usr/local/rvm/gems/jruby-1.6.2@rich_collection/gems/mongo-1.3.1/lib/../lib/mongo/collection.rb:479
            (root) at /tmp/test.rb:6
{noformat}

When I check the collection the index has been set up:

{noformat}
> db.xyz.getIndexes()
[
	{
		"name" : "_id_",
		"ns" : "fragments_20110831.xyz",
		"key" : {
			"_id" : 1
		},
		"v" : 0
	},
	{
		"name" : "split_key_1__id_1",
		"ns" : "fragments_20110831.xyz",
		"key" : {
			"split_key" : 1,
			"_id" : 1
		},
		"v" : 0
	}
]
{noformat}

There is no related output in the mongos logs, nor mongod logs (for the shard that was the primary for the database) when I ran the script.

Also, running the ensureIndex command in the mongo console results in the same strange message, and the index is set up correctly (notice I use another collection here, so it's not the same index that was created by the script):

{noformat}
> db.abc.ensureIndex({split_key: 1, _id: 1})
isOk()
> db.abc.getIndexes()
[
	{
		"name" : "_id_",
		"ns" : "fragments_20110831.abc",
		"key" : {
			"_id" : 1
		},
		"v" : 0
	},
	{
		"_id" : ObjectId("4e5f4e112c59f6dc27e04d42"),
		"ns" : "fragments_20110831.abc",
		"key" : {
			"split_key" : 1,
			"_id" : 1
		},
		"name" : "split_key_1__id_1",
		"v" : 0
	}
]
{noformat}

weirdly the index gets an {{_id}} field when created from the console.

Since this usually doesn't happen, perhaps the real bug here is a mongos issue, and the Ruby driver just doesn't handle getting the response "isOk()" and interprets this as an error message?
